'''阿尔加山'''（Mons Argaeus）是[[月球|月球]]上一座楔入在[[澄海_(月球)|澄海]]和[[澄海|澄海]]东侧边界之间的山脉<ref>{{cite book 
 | first=Peter | last=Grego | date=2004
 | title=Moon Observer's Guide | url=https://archive.org/details/fireflymoonobser00greg | publisher=Firefly Books
 | isbn=1552978885 }}</ref>，其中心[[月面坐标|月面坐标]]为北纬19.33、东经29.01<ref name=gazetteer/>，底部尺寸为65×30公里<ref>Measured on the map</ref>，峰顶高出周围[[月海|月海]]2.3-2.7公里，但较月面绝对高度为-0.29公里<ref name=JMARS>For altimetric satellite data [[月球勘测轨道飞行器|Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter]], obtained through the program[http://jmars.asu.edu JMARS] {{Wayback|url=http://jmars.asu.edu/ |date=20190122103100 }}</ref>。

==命名==
由于它在月球上靠近[[金牛山脉_(月球)|金牛山脉]]，因此，也以[[地球|地球]]上一座接近[[托鲁斯山脉|托鲁斯山脉]]<ref name=Webb_1859>{{cite book
 |title       =Celestial Objects for Common Telescopes
 |authorlink2 =Webb T. W.
 |location    =London
 |publisher   =Longman, Green, Longman, and Roberts
 |date       =1859
 |pages      =72
 |url        =http://books.google.com/books?id=5DoDAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA72&dq=Mount
}}</ref>（也译作“金牛山脉”）的山脉-古希腊名为“[[埃尔吉耶斯山|埃尔吉耶斯山]]的[[拉丁|拉丁]]名来命名（地球上的这二座山均在现今的[[土耳其|土耳其]]境内）。该山脉的英文名“Mount Argaeus”最早是在1859年由[[英国|英国]][[天文学家|天文学家]]托马斯·威廉·韦布（Thomas William Webb）提出<ref name=Webb_1859/><ref name=Whitaker_2003>{{cite book
 |title      =Mapping and Naming the Moon: A History of Lunar Cartography and Nomenclature
 |authorlink2 =Whitaker E. A.
 |publisher   =Cambridge University Press
 |date        =2003
 |isbn       =9780521544146
 |url        =http://books.google.com/books?id=aV1i27jDYL8C&pg=PA150&dq=Argaeus
 |pages      =150
 |bibcode    =2003mnm..book.....W
}}</ref>，1935年被[[国际天文学联合会|国际天文学联合会]]正式采纳<ref name=gazetteer/><ref name=Blagg_1935>{{cite book
 |title       =Named Lunar Formations
 |authorlink2 =Blagg, M. A.; Müller, K.; Wesley, W. H.; Saunder, S. A.; Franz, J.
 |location    =London
 |publisher   =P. Lund, Humphries & Co. Ltd.
 |date        =1935
 |pages       =20
 |bibcode     =1935nlf..book.....B
}}</ref>。60年代初被赋予拉丁名格式“Mons Argaeus”<ref name=Transactions_11B>{{cite book
 |title        = Transactions of the IAU Vol. XI B. Proceedings of the 11th General Assembly (Berkeley, 1961)
